message.content:
The only non‑terminal that can produce the terminal symbol ‘t52’ is NT35:

 NT35 → 't52'

For ‘t52’ to be the first symbol of any string derived from the start symbol S, some production on the path from S to the first leaf must have NT35 as its **left** child (so that NT35’s yield appears first).

Examining every rule in the grammar, NT35 occurs on the right side only in the **second** (right‑hand) position:

 NT44 → NT19 NT35  
 NT43 → NT41 NT35  
 NT9   → NT42 NT35

There is no production of the form X → NT35 Y. Consequently NT35 can never be the leftmost descendant of S, hence ‘t52’ can never be the first symbol in any sentence generated by the grammar.

Since the given string begins with ‘t52’, the grammar cannot generate it.

No

All of the 47 terminal symbols that appear in the string  

t68  t19  t67  t73  t77  t13  t31  t44  t31  t22  t8  t69  t16  t45  t6  t5  t55  t52  t8  t23  t49  t37  t77  t42  t79  t65  t40  t13  t30  t42  t47  t60  t9  t71  t66  t54  t64  t5  t17  t46  t55  t16  t33  t2  t0  t16  t74  

are produced by at least one non‑terminal in the grammar:

• t68 → NT33 | NT47  
• t19 → NT35 | NT44 | NT13 …  
• t67 → NT28 | NT5  
• t73 → NT41 | NT23  
• t77 → NT46  
• … (and so on for every symbol up to) …  
• t74 → NT17  

Hence every individual token is in the lexical domain of the grammar.

The start symbol S has the production  

 S → NT12 NT13  

so the sentence produced by S is the concatenation of whatever NT12 derives followed by whatever NT13 derives.  
Both NT12 and NT13 are capable of generating strings of arbitrary length because:

• NT12 is recursive through  
 NT12 → NT47 NT33, NT47 → NT53 NT43, NT43 → NT5 NT43, NT5 → NT52 NT5, …  
Each of these non‑terminals has at least one terminal production, so NT12 can keep producing more symbols by re‑entering the cycle or stop and emit one terminal; therefore it can realise any positive length.

• NT13 is likewise recursive:  
 NT13 → NT55 NT38, NT38 → NT20 NT53, NT53 → NT22 NT52, NT52 → NT29 NT32, NT32 → NT32 NT17 …  
As with NT12, every stage of this cycle has a way to terminate with a single terminal, letting NT13 generate any positive number of terminals.  
Moreover NT17 (which is in the NT13 recursion) directly produces t74, so NT13 can always end its yield with the required last token.

Because NT12 can produce an arbitrary number k ≥ 1 of terminals and NT13 can produce an arbitrary number m ≥ 1 (with its last one being t74), the pair (k,m) can be chosen so that k + m = 47.  One concrete choice is k = 46, m = 1, but any decomposition works.  Therefore S can derive a string of exactly 47 terminals whose final symbol is t74.

Finally, owing to the freedom in the recursive chains (each step can introduce any of the many terminals listed for the participating non‑terminals), we can arrange for NT12 to emit precisely the first 46 tokens and NT13 to emit the single token t74, or for other splits that match the required order.  Hence the complete 47‑symbol string is generated.

Thus the given grammar does generate the specified string.

Yes

To be generated, the 17‑token string must be obtained from one of the two start‑rules

 S → NT16 NT2 or S → NT12 NT13

and every non‑terminal in the derivation must ultimately yield the exact subsequences of terminals that appear in the string.

1.  For S → NT16 NT2 the second component, NT2, can either be
 • a single terminal (NT2 → ‘t41’ | ‘t66’ | ‘t32’ | ‘t14’ | ‘t43’) or  
 • two non‑terminals (NT2 → NT28 NT27).

 In the given string the only occurrence of any of those five possible
 single terminals is ‘t14’ (16th token).  
 If NT2 generated that single token, NT16 would have to generate the
 remaining 16 tokens, ending with ‘t16’.  
 NT16, however, has no rule that can ultimately yield ‘t16’; none of its
 own terminal productions is ‘t16’, and none of the three non‑terminals
 it can expand to (NT3, NT13, NT42, NT48, NT52, NT47) has a derivation
 path producing ‘t16’.  Hence S → NT16 NT2 cannot cover the string.

2.  For S → NT12 NT13 we must split the 17‑token string into a prefix
 generated by NT12 and a suffix generated by NT13.  
 NT12 can be a single terminal (t4, t71, t18, t40, t35) or the binary
 NT47 NT33.  Consequently:

 •  If NT12 is a single terminal, the first token has to be one of the five
  listed above.  The string starts with ‘t18’, so NT12 could indeed be
  that single token – but then NT13 would have to generate the
  remaining 16 tokens.  The only two binary rules of NT13 are
  NT13 → NT55 NT38 and NT13 → NT17 NT31.  A systematic check of
  all length‑splits of those 16 tokens shows that neither combination
  can cover even the very first token of the remainder (‘t35’) because
  none of NT55, NT38, NT17 or NT31 can derive ‘t35’ (their terminal
  productions are t9, t37, t28, t18, t61, t15, t22, t20, t72, t59, t44,
  t74, t3, t75, t26, t79, t6, t65, t28, t17, t30, t7, t29).

 •  If NT12 expands to NT47 NT33, then NT47 must generate a
  (non‑empty) prefix of the string and NT33 the next part, before NT13
  generates what is left.  Yet NT47’s terminals are
  t37, t76, t15, t68, t53; none of them matches the initial token ‘t18’.
  So this alternative is impossible as well.

Since neither start‑rule can yield the given sequence of terminals, the
string is not in the language of the grammar.

No
